      "question": "In $\\triangle ABC$ and $\\triangle DEF$, it is given that $\\angle A = \\angle D$ and $\\angle B = \\angle E$. If the side lengths are $AB = 3$ $\\text{cm}$, $AC = 4$ $\\text{cm}$, $DE = 4.5$ $\\text{cm}$, and $EF = 6$ $\\text{cm}$, which of the following statements is true?",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify that since $\\angle A = \\angle D$ and $\\angle B = \\angle E$, the triangles $\\triangle ABC$ and $\\triangle DEF$ are similar by the AA (Angle-Angle) similarity criterion.",
          "State the property of similar triangles: their corresponding sides must be in the same ratio.",
          "Check the ratio of the sides: $\\frac{AB}{DE} = \\frac{3}{4.5} = \\frac{2}{3}$.",
          "Check the ratio $\\frac{AC}{DF} = \\frac{2}{3}$. Thus, $DF = AC \\times \\frac{3}{2} = 4 \\times 1.5 = 6$ $\\text{cm}$.",
          "Check the ratio $\\frac{BC}{EF} = \\frac{2}{3}$. Thus, $BC = EF \\times \\frac{2}{3} = 6 \\times \\frac{2}{3} = 4$ $\\text{cm}$.",
          "Conclude that $\\triangle ABC \\sim \\triangle DEF$ and verify the corresponding side relationships."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\angle A = \\angle D, \\angle B = \\angle E \\Rightarrow \\triangle ABC \\sim \\triangle DEF \\text{ (by AA similarity)} \\\\ \\frac{AB}{DE} = \\frac{BC}{EF} = \\frac{AC}{DF} \\\\ \\frac{3}{4.5} = \\frac{BC}{6} = \\frac{4}{DF} \\\\ \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{BC}{6} \\Rightarrow BC = 4 \\text{ cm} \\\\ \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{4}{DF} \\Rightarrow DF = 6 \\text{ cm}$"
      },
      "topic": "Triangles",
